		console.time('test');
		var precache_from_extension = false;
		if (window.location.hash.indexOf('precache_from_extension=true') > -1) {
			precache_from_extension = true;
		}
		var pageLoadStart = new Date().getTime();
		var pageHTMLReceived = (new Date()).getTime();
		var genericData = {
			debug: {
				pageLoadedTimestamp: (new Date()).getTime()
			}
		};
		var localContentHtml;
		var localContentHtmlPartial;
		var attempts = 0;
		function tempConditioning(mystring) {
			//this is to migrate old article contents until we do a database recaching (advance version)
			//replace old pic-placeholder with one which supports both protocols
			if (location.protocol == 'https:') {
				var newstring = mystring.split('http://assets.cdn.wikiwand.com/img/pic-placeholder.gif').join('//d3isfnyiuldmfu.cloudfront.net/img/pic-placeholder.gif');
			} else {
				newstring = mystring;
			}
			return newstring;
		}

		function httpGet(theUrl, type) {
			var xmlHttp = null;
			xmlHttp = new XMLHttpRequest();
			xmlHttp.onreadystatechange = function() {
				if (xmlHttp.readyState == 4) // Finished
				{
					if (xmlHttp.status == 200) {
						if (theUrl.indexOf('_PARTIAL_DOWNLOAD') == -1) {
							//console.log('got full text');
							localContentHtml = xmlHttp.responseText;
						} else {
							//console.log('got partial text');
							localContentHtmlPartial = xmlHttp.responseText;
						}
					}
					else {
						console.log('failed with status ',xmlHttp.status);
						attempts++;
						if (attempts < 10 && (theUrl.indexOf('_PARTIAL_DOWNLOAD') == -1)) {
							console.log("DOWNLOAD FAILED, TRYING AGAIN ", theUrl);
							if (xmlHttp.status == 0) {
								if (theUrl.indexOf('s3.amazonaws.com') != -1) {
									if (attempts==9) {

										setTimeout(function() {
											var element;
											if (typeof(noAdblock) == 'undefined') {
												element = '#adblockNotice';
											} else {
												element = '#httpsEverywhereNotice';
											}
											if ($(element).length > 0) {
												console.log(' element exists');
												$(element).show();
												$(element).css('opacity', 1);
												$(element).detach().prependTo('#content');
											}
										}, 6000);
									}
								}
								var urlOnS3 = 'https://s3.amazonaws.com/ww-article-cache-1/en/HTML';
								urlOnS3 = urlOnS3.replace('http://', '//').replace('https://', '//');
								urlOnS3 = urlOnS3.replace(/\+/g, '%2B');
								httpGet(urlOnS3, 'html');
								httpGet(urlOnS3, 'html');
							} else {
								//console.log('status ', xmlHttp);
								setTimeout(function() {
									httpGet(theUrl, 'html');
								}, 500);
							}
						}
					}
				}
			};
			xmlHttp.open("GET", theUrl, true);
			xmlHttp.send(null);
		}
	
[End Tag        ] </script

[Attribute Value] HyperText Markup Language, commonly referred to as HTML, is the standard markup language used to create web pages.[1] It is written in the form of HTML elements consisting of tags enclosed in angle brackets . HTML tags most commonly come in pairs like &lt;h1&gt; and &lt;/h1&gt;, although some tags represent empty elements and so are unpaired, for example &lt;img&gt;. The first tag in a pair is the start tag, and the second tag is the end tag .

[Text           ] from 1990 he listed
[Start Tag      ] <sup
[Attribute Name ] id

[Text           ] "some of the many areas in which hypertext is used" and put an encyclopedia first.

[Start Tag      ] <p
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] The first publicly available description of HTML was a document called "HTML Tags", first mentioned on the Internet by Berners-Lee in late 1991.
[Start Tag      ] <sup
[Attribute Name ] id
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] cite_ref-tagshtml_6-0
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] reference
[Tag End        ] >

[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =

[Equal Sign     ] =

[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] [
[End Tag        ] </span
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] 6
[Start Tag      ] <span
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] ]
[End Tag        ] </span
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </sup
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <sup
[Attribute Name ] id
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] cite_ref-7
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] reference
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://www.wikiwand.com/en/HTML#citenote7
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] anch-link
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <span
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] [
[End Tag        ] </span
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] 7
[Start Tag      ] <span
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] ]
[End Tag        ] </span
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </sup
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] It describes 18 elements comprising the initial, relatively simple design of HTML. Except for the hyperlink tag, these were strongly influenced by
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://www.wikiwand.com/en/SGMLguid
[Attribute Name ] title
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] SGMLguid
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] int-link
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] SGMLguid
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] , an in-house
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://www.wikiwand.com/en/Standard_Generalized_Markup_Language
[Attribute Name ] title
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] Standard Generalized Markup Language
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] int-link
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] Standard Generalized Markup Language
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] (SGML)-based documentation format at CERN. Eleven of these elements still exist in HTML 4.
[Start Tag      ] <sup
[Attribute Name ] id
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] cite_ref-8
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] reference
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =

[Equal Sign     ] =

[Tag End        ] >

[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] [
[End Tag        ] </span
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] 8
[Start Tag      ] <span
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] ]
[End Tag        ] </span
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </sup
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </p
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <p
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] HTML is a
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://www.wikiwand.com/en/Markup_language
[Attribute Name ] title
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] Markup language
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] int-link
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] markup language
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] that
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://www.wikiwand.com/en/Web_browser
[Attribute Name ] title
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] Web browser
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] int-link
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] web browsers
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] use to interpret and
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://www.wikiwand.com/en/Typesetting
[Attribute Name ] title
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] Typesetting
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] int-link
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] compose
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] text, images and other material into visual or audible web pages. Default characteristics for every item of HTML markup are defined in the browser, and these characteristics can be altered or enhanced by the web page designer's additional use of
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://www.wikiwand.com/en/Cascading_Style_Sheets
[Attribute Name ] title
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] Cascading Style Sheets
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] int-link
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] CSS
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] . Many of the text elements are found in the 1988 ISO technical report TR 9537
[Start Tag      ] <i
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] Techniques for using SGML
[End Tag        ] </i
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] , which in turn covers the features of early text formatting languages such as that used by the
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://www.wikiwand.com/en/TYPSET_and_RUNOFF
[Attribute Name ] title
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] TYPSET and RUNOFF
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] int-link
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] RUNOFF command
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] developed in the early 1960s for the
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://www.wikiwand.com/en/Compatible_Time-Sharing_System
[Attribute Name ] title
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] Compatible Time-Sharing System
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] int-link
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] CTSS
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] (Compatible Time-Sharing System) operating system: these formatting commands were derived from the commands used by typesetters to manually format documents. However, the SGML concept of generalized markup is based on elements (nested annotated ranges with attributes) rather than merely print effects, with also the separation of structure and markup; HTML has been progressively moved in this direction with CSS.
[End Tag        ] </p
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <p
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] Berners-Lee considered HTML to be an application of SGML. It was formally defined as such by the
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://www.wikiwand.com/en/Internet_Engineering_Task_Force
[Attribute Name ] title
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] Internet Engineering Task Force
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] int-link
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] Internet Engineering Task Force
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] (IETF) with the mid-1993 publication of the first proposal for an HTML specification:
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] rel
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] nofollow
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] external text ext-link
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://www.w3.org/MarkUp/draft-ietf-iiir-html-01.txt
[Attribute Name ] target
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] _blank
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] "Hypertext Markup Language (HTML)" Internet-Draft
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] by Berners-Lee and
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://www.wikiwand.com/en/Dan_Connolly_(computer_scientist)
[Attribute Name ] title
[Equal Sign     ] =

[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] int-link
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] Dan Connolly
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] , which included an SGML
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://www.wikiwand.com/en/Document_Type_Definition
[Attribute Name ] title
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] Document Type Definition
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] mw-redirect int-link
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] Document Type Definition
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] to define the grammar.
[Start Tag      ] <sup
[Attribute Name ] id
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] cite_ref-9
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] reference
[Tag End        ] >

[End Tag        ] </span
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </sup
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] The draft expired after six months, but was notable for its acknowledgment of the
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://www.wikiwand.com/en/Mosaic_(web_browser)
[Attribute Name ] title
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] Mosaic (web browser)

[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] int-link
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] NCSA Mosaic
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] browser's custom tag for embedding in-line images, reflecting the IETF's philosophy of basing standards on successful prototypes.
[Start Tag      ] <sup
[Attribute Name ] id
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] cite_ref-raymond_10-0
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] reference
[Tag End        ] >

[Tag End        ] >

[Tag End        ] >

[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] 10
[Start Tag      ] <span
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] ]
[End Tag        ] </span
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </sup
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] Similarly,
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://www.wikiwand.com/en/Dave_Raggett

[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] 's competing Internet-Draft, "HTML+ (Hypertext Markup Format)", from late 1993, suggested standardizing already-implemented features like tables and fill-out forms.
[Start Tag      ] <sup

[Start Tag      ] <p
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] After the HTML and HTML+ drafts expired in early 1994, the IETF created an HTML Working Group, which in 1995 completed "HTML 2.0", the first HTML specification intended to be treated as a standard against which future implementations should be based.
[Start Tag      ] <sup
[Attribute Name ] id
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] cite_ref-12

[Equal Sign     ] =

[Start Tag      ] <p
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] Further development under the auspices of the IETF was stalled by competing interests. Since 1996, the HTML specifications have been maintained, with input from commercial software vendors, by the
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://www.wikiwand.com/en/World_Wide_Web_Consortium
[Attribute Name ] title
[Equal Sign     ] =

[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] int-link
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] World Wide Web Consortium
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] (W3C).
[Start Tag      ] <sup
[Attribute Name ] id
[Equal Sign     ] =

[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] reference

[End Tag        ] </span
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </sup
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] However, in 2000, HTML also became an international standard (
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://www.wikiwand.com/en/International_Organization_for_Standardization

[Tag End        ] >

[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://www.wikiwand.com/en/International_Electrotechnical_Commission
[Attribute Name ] title
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] International Electrotechnical Commission
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] int-link
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] IEC
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] 15445:2000). HTML 4.01 was published in late 1999, with further errata published through 2001. In 2004 development began on HTML5 in the
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href

[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] (WHATWG), which became a joint deliverable with the W3C in 2008, and completed and standardized on 28 October 2014.

[Text           ] On 14 February 2011, the W3C extended the charter of its
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] rel
[Equal Sign     ] =

[Text           ] HTML Working Group
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] with clear milestones for HTML5. In May 2011, the working group advanced HTML5 to "Last Call", an invitation to communities inside and outside W3C to confirm the technical soundness of the specification. The W3C is developing a comprehensive test suite to achieve broad interoperability for the full specification by 2014, which is now the target date for Recommendation.

[Start Tag      ] <p
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] HTML documents imply a structure of nested
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://www.wikiwand.com/en/HTML_element
[Attribute Name ] title
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] HTML element
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] int-link
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] HTML elements
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] . These are indicated in the document by HTML
[Start Tag      ] <i
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] tags
[End Tag        ] </i
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] , enclosed in angle brackets thus:
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] nowrap
[Attribute Name ] style
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] 
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] &lt;p&gt;
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <sup
[Attribute Name ] id
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] cite_ref-48
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] reference
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://www.wikiwand.com/en/HTML#citenote48
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] anch-link
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <span
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] [
[End Tag        ] </span
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] 48
[Start Tag      ] <span
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] ]
[End Tag        ] </span
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </sup
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </p
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <p
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] In the simple, general case, the extent of an element is indicated by a pair of tags: a "start tag"
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] nowrap
[Attribute Name ] style
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] 
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] &lt;p&gt;
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] and "end tag"
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] nowrap
[Attribute Name ] style
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] 
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] &lt;/p&gt;
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] . The text content of the element, if any, is placed between these tags.
[End Tag        ] </p
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <p
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] Tags may also enclose further tag markup between the start and end, including a mixture of tags and text. This indicates further, nested, elements, as children of the parent element.
[End Tag        ] </p
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <p
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] The start tag may also include
[Start Tag      ] <i
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] attributes
[End Tag        ] </i
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] within the tag. These indicate other information, such as identifiers for sections within the document, identifiers used to bind style information to the presentation of the document, and for some tags such as the
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] nowrap
[Attribute Name ] style
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] 
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] &lt;img&gt;
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] used to embed images, the reference to the image resource.
[End Tag        ] </p
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <p
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] Some elements, such as the
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://www.wikiwand.com/en/Line_breaking_character
[Attribute Name ] title
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] Line breaking character
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] mw-redirect int-link
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] line break
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] nowrap
[Attribute Name ] style
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] 
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] &lt;br&gt;
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] , do not permit
[Start Tag      ] <i
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] any
[End Tag        ] </i
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] embedded content, either text or further tags. These require only a single empty tag (akin to a start tag) and do not use an end tag.
[End Tag        ] </p
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <p
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] Many tags, particularly the closing end tag for the very commonly-used paragraph element
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] nowrap
[Attribute Name ] style
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] 
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] &lt;p&gt;
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] , are optional. An HTML browser or other agent can infer the closure for the end of an element from the context and the structural rules defined by the HTML standard. These rules are complex and not widely understood by most HTML coders.
[End Tag        ] </p
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <p
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] The general form of an
[Start Tag      ] <b
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] HTML element
[End Tag        ] </b
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] is therefore:
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] &lt;tag attribute1="value1" attribute2="value2"&gt;
[Start Tag      ] <i
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] content
[End Tag        ] </i
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] &lt;/tag&gt;
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] . Some HTML elements are defined as
[Start Tag      ] <i
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] empty elements
[End Tag        ] </i
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] and take the form
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] &lt;tag attribute1="value1" attribute2="value2" &gt;
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] . Empty elements may enclose no content, for instance, the BR tag or the inline IMG tag. The name of an HTML element is the name used in the tags. Note that the end tag's name is preceded by a slash character, "/", and that in empty elements the end tag is neither required nor allowed. If attributes are not mentioned, default values are used in each case.
[End Tag        ] </p
[Tag End        ] >

[Tag End        ] >

[Equal Sign     ] =

[Text           ] Line breaks:
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] nowrap
[Attribute Name ] style
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] 
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] &lt;br&gt;
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] . The difference between
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] nowrap
[Attribute Name ] style
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] 
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] &lt;br&gt;
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] and
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] nowrap
[Attribute Name ] style
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] 
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] &lt;p&gt;
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] is that "br"
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://www.wikiwand.com/en/Line_breaking_character
[Attribute Name ] title
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] Line breaking character
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] mw-redirect int-link
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] breaks a line
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] without altering the semantic structure of the page, whereas "p" sections the page into
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://www.wikiwand.com/en/Paragraph
[Attribute Name ] title
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] Paragraph
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] int-link
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] paragraphs
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] . Note also that "br" is an
[Start Tag      ] <i
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] empty element
[End Tag        ] </i
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] in that, while it may have attributes, it can take no content and it may not have an end tag.
[End Tag        ] </p
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <div
[Attribute Name ] dir
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] ltr
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] mw-geshi mw-code mw-content-ltr
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <div
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] html4strict source-html4strict
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <pre
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] de1 hljs vim
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <span
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] sc2
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] &lt;
[Start Tag      ] <span
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] kw2
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <span
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] hljs-keyword
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] p
[End Tag        ] </span
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </span
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] &gt;
[End Tag        ] </span
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] This
[Start Tag      ] <span
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] sc2
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] &lt;
[Start Tag      ] <span
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] kw2
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <span
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =

[End Tag        ] </span

[End Tag        ] </span

[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <span
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] hljs-keyword
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] is
[End Tag        ] </span
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <span
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] hljs-keyword
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] a
[End Tag        ] </span
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] paragraph

[Start Tag      ] <p
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] There are several types of markup elements used in HTML:
[End Tag        ] </p
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <dl
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <dt
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] Structural markup describes the purpose of text
[End Tag        ] </dt
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <dd
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] For example,
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] nowrap
[Attribute Name ] style
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] 
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] &lt;h2&gt;Golf&lt;/h2&gt;
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] establishes "Golf" as a second-level
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://www.wikiwand.com/en/HTML_element#Basic_text

[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] HTML element
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] int-link
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] heading
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] . Structural markup does not denote any specific rendering, but most web browsers have default styles for element formatting. Content may be further styled using
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://www.wikiwand.com/en/Cascading_Style_Sheets
[Attribute Name ] title
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] Cascading Style Sheets
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] int-link
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] Cascading Style Sheets
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] (CSS).
[Start Tag      ] <sup
[Attribute Name ] id
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] cite_ref-49

[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] reference
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <a

[Tag End        ] >

[Start Tag      ] <dt
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] Presentational markup describes the appearance of the text, regardless of its purpose
[End Tag        ] </dt
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <dd
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] For example
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] nowrap
[Attribute Name ] style
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] 
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] &lt;b&gt;boldface&lt;/b&gt;
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] indicates that visual output devices should render "boldface" in bold text, but gives little indication what devices that are unable to do this (such as aural devices that read the text aloud) should do. In the case of both
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] nowrap
[Attribute Name ] style
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] 
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] &lt;b&gt;bold&lt;/b&gt;
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] and
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] nowrap
[Attribute Name ] style
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] 
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] &lt;i&gt;italic&lt;/i&gt;
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] , there are other elements that may have equivalent visual renderings but which are more semantic in nature, such as
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] nowrap
[Attribute Name ] style
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] 
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] &lt;strong&gt;strong text&lt;/strong&gt;
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] and
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] nowrap
[Attribute Name ] style
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] 
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] &lt;em&gt;emphasised text&lt;/em&gt;
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] respectively. It is easier to see how an aural user agent should interpret the latter two elements. However, they are not equivalent to their presentational counterparts: it would be undesirable for a screen-reader to emphasize the name of a book, for instance, but on a screen such a name would be italicized. Most presentational markup elements have become

[Text           ] There are several common attributes that may appear in many elements&nbsp;:
[End Tag        ] </p
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <ul
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <li
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] The
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] id
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] attribute provides a document-wide unique identifier for an element. This is used to identify the element so that stylesheets can alter its presentational properties, and scripts may alter, animate or delete its contents or presentation. Appended to the URL of the page, it provides a globally unique identifier for the element, typically a sub-section of the page. For example, the ID "Attributes" in
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HTML#Attributes
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </li
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <li
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] The
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] class
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] attribute provides a way of classifying similar elements. This can be used for
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://www.wikiwand.com/en/Semantics
[Attribute Name ] title
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] Semantics
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] int-link
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] semantic
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] or presentation purposes. For example, an HTML document might semantically use the designation
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] class="notation"
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] to indicate that all elements with this class value are subordinate to the main text of the document. In presentation, such elements might be gathered together and presented as footnotes on a page instead of appearing in the place where they occur in the HTML source. Class attributes are used semantically in
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://www.wikiwand.com/en/Microformat
[Attribute Name ] title
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] Microformat
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] int-link
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] microformats
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] . Multiple class values may be specified; for example
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] class="notation important"
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] puts the element into both the "notation" and the "important" classes.
[End Tag        ] </li
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <li
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] An author may use the
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] style
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] attribute to assign presentational properties to a particular element. It is considered better practice to use an element's
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] id
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] or
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] class
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] attributes to select the element from within a stylesheet, though sometimes this can be too cumbersome for a simple, specific, or ad hoc styling.
[End Tag        ] </li
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <li
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] The
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] title
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] attribute is used to attach subtextual explanation to an element. In most browsers this attribute is displayed as a
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://www.wikiwand.com/en/Tooltip
[Attribute Name ] title
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] Tooltip
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] int-link
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] tooltip
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] .
[End Tag        ] </li
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <li
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] The
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] lang
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] attribute identifies the natural language of the element's contents, which may be different from that of the rest of the document. For example, in an English-language document:

[Text           ] Most elements take the language-related attribute

[Text           ] to specify text direction, such as with "rtl" for right-to-left text in, for example,

[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <h3
[Tag End        ] >

[Equal Sign     ] =

[Text           ] Character and entity references
[End Tag        ] </span

[Tag End        ] >

[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </td
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <td
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <p
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] See also:
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://www.wikiwand.com/en/List_of_XML_and_HTML_character_entity_references
[Attribute Name ] title
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] List of XML and HTML character entity references
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] int-link
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] List of XML and HTML character entity references
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] and
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://www.wikiwand.com/en/Unicode_and_HTML
[Attribute Name ] title
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] Unicode and HTML
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] int-link
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] Unicode and HTML
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </p
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </td
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </tr
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </tbody
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </table
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <p
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] As of version 4.0, HTML defines a set of 252
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://www.wikiwand.com/en/Character_entity_reference
[Attribute Name ] title
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] Character entity reference
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] mw-redirect int-link
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] character entity references
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] and a set of 1,114,050
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://www.wikiwand.com/en/Numeric_character_reference
[Attribute Name ] title
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] Numeric character reference
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] int-link
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] numeric character references
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] , both of which allow individual characters to be written via simple markup, rather than literally. A literal character and its markup counterpart are considered equivalent and are rendered identically.
[End Tag        ] </p
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <p
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] The ability to "escape" characters in this way allows for the characters
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] &lt;
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] and
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] &amp;
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] (when written as
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] &amp;lt;
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] and
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] &amp;amp;
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] , respectively) to be interpreted as character data, rather than markup. For example, a literal
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] &lt;
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] normally indicates the start of a tag, and
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] &amp;
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] normally indicates the start of a character entity reference or numeric character reference; writing it as
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] &amp;amp;
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] or
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] &amp;#x26;
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] or
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] &amp;#38;
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] allows
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] &amp;
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] to be included in the content of an element or in the value of an attribute. The double-quote character (
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] "
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] ), when not used to quote an attribute value, must also be escaped as
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] &amp;quot;
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] or
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] &amp;#x22;
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] or
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] &amp;#34;
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] when it appears within the attribute value itself. Equivalently, the single-quote character (
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] '
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] ), when not used to quote an attribute value, must also be escaped as
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] &amp;#x27;
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] or
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] &amp;#39;
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] (or as
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] &amp;apos;
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] in HTML5 or XHTML documents
[Start Tag      ] <sup
[Attribute Name ] id
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] cite_ref-55
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] reference
[Tag End        ] >

[Equal Sign     ] =

[Equal Sign     ] =

[Tag End        ] >

[End Tag        ] </span

[Text           ] 55
[Start Tag      ] <span
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] ]
[End Tag        ] </span
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </sup
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <sup
[Attribute Name ] id
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] cite_ref-aposhtml_56-0
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] reference
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://www.wikiwand.com/en/HTML#citenoteaposhtml56

[Equal Sign     ] =

[Tag End        ] >

[Text           ] 56

[Text           ] ]
[End Tag        ] </span
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </sup
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] ) when it appears within the attribute value itself. If document authors overlook the need to escape such characters, some browsers can be very forgiving and try to use context to guess their intent. The result is still invalid markup, which makes the document less accessible to other browsers and to other
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://www.wikiwand.com/en/User_agent

[Equal Sign     ] =

[Equal Sign     ] =

[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] user agents
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] that may try to parse the document for
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://www.wikiwand.com/en/Web_crawler
[Attribute Name ] title
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] Web crawler
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] int-link
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] search and indexing
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] purposes for example.
[End Tag        ] </p
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <p
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] Escaping also allows for characters that are not easily typed, or that are not available in the document's
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://www.wikiwand.com/en/Character_encoding
[Attribute Name ] title
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] Character encoding
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] int-link
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] character encoding
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] , to be represented within element and attribute content. For example, the acute-accented
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] e
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] (
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] é
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] ), a character typically found only on Western European and South American keyboards, can be written in any HTML document as the entity reference
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] &amp;eacute;
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] or as the numeric references
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] &amp;#xE9;
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] or
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] &amp;#233;
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] , using characters that are available on all keyboards and are supported in all character encodings.
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://www.wikiwand.com/en/Unicode

[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =

[Equal Sign     ] =

[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] int-link
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] UTF-8
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] are compatible with all modern browsers and allow direct access to almost all the characters of the world's writing systems.

[Start Tag      ] <h3
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <span
[Attribute Name ] class

[Start Tag      ] <p
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] HTML defines several
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://www.wikiwand.com/en/Data_type

[Equal Sign     ] =

All of these data types are specializations of character data.
[End Tag        ] </p
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <h3
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <span
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] mw-headline

[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] Document_type_declaration
[Tag End        ] >

[End Tag        ] </span
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </h3
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <p
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] HTML documents are required to start with a
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://www.wikiwand.com/en/Document_Type_Declaration
[Attribute Name ] title
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] Document Type Declaration
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] mw-redirect int-link
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] Document Type Declaration
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] (informally, a "doctype"). In browsers, the doctype helps to define the rendering mode—particularly whether to use
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://www.wikiwand.com/en/Quirks_mode
[Attribute Name ] title
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] Quirks mode
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] int-link
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] quirks mode
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] .
[End Tag        ] </p
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <p
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] The original purpose of the doctype was to enable parsing and validation of HTML documents by SGML tools based on the
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://www.wikiwand.com/en/Document_Type_Definition
[Attribute Name ] title
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] Document Type Definition
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] mw-redirect int-link
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] Document Type Definition
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] (DTD). The DTD to which the DOCTYPE refers contains a machine-readable grammar specifying the permitted and prohibited content for a document conforming to such a DTD. Browsers, on the other hand, do not implement HTML as an application of SGML and by consequence do not read the DTD.
[End Tag        ] </p
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <p
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://www.wikiwand.com/en/HTML5
[Attribute Name ] title
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] HTML5
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] int-link
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] HTML5
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] does not define a DTD; therefore, in HTML5 the doctype declaration is simpler and shorter:
[Start Tag      ] <sup
[Attribute Name ] id
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] cite_ref-58
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] reference
[Tag End        ] >

[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://www.wikiwand.com/en/HTML#citenote58

[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] anch-link
[Tag End        ] >

[Tag End        ] >

[End Tag        ] </span
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] 58
[Start Tag      ] <span
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] ]
[End Tag        ] </span
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </sup
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </p
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <div
[Attribute Name ] dir

[Text           ] An example of an HTML 4 doctype

[Tag End        ] >

[Start Tag      ] <p
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] This declaration references the DTD for the "strict" version of HTML 4.01. SGML-based validators read the DTD in order to properly parse the document and to perform validation. In modern browsers, a valid doctype activates standards mode as opposed to
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://www.wikiwand.com/en/Quirks_mode
[Attribute Name ] title
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] Quirks mode
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] int-link
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] quirks mode
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] .
[End Tag        ] </p
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <p
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] In addition, HTML 4.01 provides Transitional and Frameset DTDs,
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://www.wikiwand.com/en/HTML#Transitional_versus_strict
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] anch-link
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] as explained below
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] . Transitional type is the most inclusive, incorporating current tags as well as older or "deprecated" tags, with the Strict DTD excluding deprecated tags. Frameset has all tags necessary to make frames on a page along with the tags included in transitional type

[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </p
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </section
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <section
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =

[Text           ] Main article:
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://www.wikiwand.com/en/Semantic_HTML
[Attribute Name ] title
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] Semantic HTML

[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] int-link

[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </p

[End Tag        ] </td
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </tr
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </tbody
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </table
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <p
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] Semantic HTML is a way of writing HTML that emphasizes the meaning of the encoded information over its presentation (look). HTML has included semantic markup from its inception,
[Start Tag      ] <sup
[Attribute Name ] id
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] cite_ref-60
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] reference
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://www.wikiwand.com/en/HTML#citenote60
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] anch-link
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <span
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] [
[End Tag        ] </span
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] 60
[Start Tag      ] <span
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] ]
[End Tag        ] </span
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </sup
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] but has also included presentational markup, such as
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] &lt;font&gt;
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] ,
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] &lt;i&gt;
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] and
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] &lt;center&gt;
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] tags. There are also the semantically neutral
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://www.wikiwand.com/en/Span_and_div

[Equal Sign     ] =

[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] tags. Since the late 1990s when
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href

[Tag End        ] >

[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] were beginning to work in most browsers, web authors have been encouraged to avoid the use of presentational HTML markup with a view to the
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =

[Equal Sign     ] =

[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] .
[Start Tag      ] <sup
[Attribute Name ] id
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] cite_ref-61

[Equal Sign     ] =

[Tag End        ] >

[Tag End        ] >

[End Tag        ] </span
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] 61

[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] ]
[End Tag        ] </span
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </sup
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </p
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <p
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] In a 2001 discussion of the
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href

[Tag End        ] >

[Attribute Name ] id
[Equal Sign     ] =

[End Tag        ] </span
[Tag End        ] >

[Tag End        ] >

[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] Such agents are not commonplace even now, but some of the ideas of
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =

[Equal Sign     ] =

[Text           ] Web 2.0
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] ,
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://www.wikiwand.com/en/Mashup_(web_application_hybrid)
[Attribute Name ] title
[Equal Sign     ] =

[Equal Sign     ] =

[End Tag        ] </a

[Text           ] and
[Start Tag      ] <a

[Text           ] of the specific data they wish to mash, compare and combine.
[End Tag        ] </p

[Start Tag      ] <p
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] An important type of web agent that does crawl and read web pages automatically, without prior knowledge of what it might find, is the
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =

[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =

[Start Tag      ] <a

[End Tag        ] </a

[Text           ] without which the World Wide Web's usefulness would be greatly reduced.
[End Tag        ] </p
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <p
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] In order for search-engine spiders to be able to rate the significance of pieces of text they find in HTML documents, and also for those creating mashups and other hybrids as well as for more automated agents as they are developed, the semantic structures that exist in HTML need to be widely and uniformly applied to bring out the meaning of published text.
[Start Tag      ] <sup
[Attribute Name ] id
[Equal Sign     ] =

[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] Presentational markup tags are
[Start Tag      ] <a

[Start Tag      ] <p
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] Good semantic HTML also improves the
[Start Tag      ] <a

[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://www.wikiwand.com/en/Accessibility
[Attribute Name ] title
[Equal Sign     ] =

[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] of web documents (see also
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://www.wikiwand.com/en/Web_Content_Accessibility_Guidelines
[Attribute Name ] title
[Equal Sign     ] =

[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] int-link

[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] ). For example, when a screen reader or audio browser can correctly ascertain the structure of a document, it will not waste the visually impaired user's time by reading out repeated or irrelevant information when it has been marked up correctly.
[End Tag        ] </p

[Text           ] ) and the character encoding (see

[Start Tag      ] <p
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] In modern browsers, the MIME type that is sent with the HTML document may affect how the document is initially interpreted. A document sent with the XHTML MIME type is expected to be
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =

[Text           ] well-formed
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] XML; syntax errors may cause the browser to fail to render it. The same document sent with the HTML MIME type might be displayed successfully, since some browsers are more lenient with HTML.
[End Tag        ] </p
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <p
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] The W3C recommendations state that XHTML 1.0 documents that follow guidelines set forth in the recommendation's Appendix C may be labeled with either MIME Type.

[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] XHTML 1.1 also states that XHTML 1.1 documents should

[Start Tag      ] <p
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] Most graphical email clients allow the use of a subset of HTML (often ill-defined) to provide formatting and
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://www.wikiwand.com/en/Semantic_web

[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] Semantic web
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] mw-redirect int-link
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] semantic
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] markup not available with
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://www.wikiwand.com/en/Plain_text
[Attribute Name ] title
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] Plain text

[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] int-link
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] plain text
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] . This may include typographic information like coloured headings, emphasized and quoted text, inline images and diagrams. Many such clients include both a
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://www.wikiwand.com/en/Graphical_user_interface

[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] Graphical user interface
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] int-link
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] GUI
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] editor for composing HTML e-mail messages and a rendering engine for displaying them. Use of HTML in e-mail is criticized by some because of compatibility issues, because it can help disguise

[Text           ] attacks, because of accessibility issues for blind or visually impaired people, because it can confuse

[Text           ] The most common

[Text           ] Main article:

[Start Tag      ] <p
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] An HTML Application (HTA; file extension ".hta") is a
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://www.wikiwand.com/en/Microsoft_Windows
[Attribute Name ] title
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] Microsoft Windows

[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] application that uses HTML and Dynamic HTML in a browser to provide the application's graphical interface. A regular HTML file is confined to the security model of the
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://www.wikiwand.com/en/Browser_security

[Equal Sign     ] =

[Equal Sign     ] =

[Text           ] , communicating only to web servers and manipulating only webpage objects and
[Start Tag      ] <a

[Equal Sign     ] =

[Tag End        ] >

[Text           ] . An HTA runs as a fully trusted application and therefore has more privileges, like creation/editing/removal of files and
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =

[Tag End        ] >

[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] entries. Because they operate outside the browser's security model, HTAs cannot be executed via HTTP, but must be downloaded (just like an
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =

[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] ) and executed from local file system.
[End Tag        ] </p
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </section
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <section
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] article_content
[Attribute Name ] id
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] section_HTML4_variations
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <h2
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <span
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] mw-headline
[Attribute Name ] id
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] HTML4_variations
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] HTML4 variations
[End Tag        ] </span
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </h2
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <div
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =

[Attribute Name ] style
[Equal Sign     ] =

[Tag End        ] >

[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <p
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] HTML is precisely what we were trying to PREVENT— ever-breaking links, links going outward only, quotes you can't follow to their origins, no version management, no rights management.
[End Tag        ] </p
[Tag End        ] >

[Attribute Name ] style

[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =

[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] Ted Nelson
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =

[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] Ted Nelson
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <sup
[Attribute Name ] id
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] cite_ref-68
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] reference
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://www.wikiwand.com/en/HTML#citenote68
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] anch-link
[Tag End        ] >
